description: A formal or polite address, often found in formal speech, titles, or written communication, typically using phrases or words that show respect or courtesy, such as "ladies" and "gentlemen".
"Lady" is often used as an honorific title for a woman, typically as part of a proper noun, such as the name of a team, organization, or title of a person.
The tokens represent the names of institutions, mostly "Notre Dame" and sometimes "Our Lady", which are often part of proper nouns.
The token "first" is often used to indicate a position or rank, often referring to a person or entity holding a primary or top position, such as the "First Lady" or in a sequence or hierarchy.
Articles, possessive pronouns, and prepositions often used in titles, particularly in names of books, movies, and organizations, often with "Lord" or "Lady" as part of the title.
The token "Lady" (or variations of it) is often used as a title of respect, honor, or courtesy, often referring to a woman.

The word "Lady" appears in various contexts, often as a title of respect or a proper noun, and is frequently used in formal or old-fashioned expressions, such as "Ladies" or "Lady" as a title of respect, and also as part of names of organizations or groups.
Titles of honor or respect, often followed by a person's name and signifying their position or rank in society, such as "Lord", "Lady", "Earl", "Prince", "General", and "Admiral".
Words related to people, especially "guys", "girls", "boys", and "ladies", often used as informal or colloquial expressions.
Often the most important words are team names or titles that include a descriptive word before the name, such as "Lady" or a color.
Names of female servants or ladies, particularly "maid" and "maiden", often used in various contexts.
Titles of nobility, predominantly "Lord", "Lady", and "Sir", used to address or refer to individuals holding high social or ceremonial positions.
Honorific titles ("Lord", "Lady") and other titles or words often used in formal or official contexts.
Titles of honor or nobility such as Lord, Lady, or Duke.
Titles of respect or courtesy, such as "Miss", "Mr.", "Mrs.", and "Lady", often used to address or refer to individuals, sometimes in formal or professional settings.

Common nouns referring to groups of people, often with a specific characteristic, such as "men", "boys", "people", "children", "players", "drivers", "Russians", "pilots", "ladies", "companies", "CEOs", "colleges", "universities", "retailers", and "Congress".

The honored text often involves terms of address, particularly formal titles used to address or refer to people, including "ladies", "gentlemen", and variations of these terms, often used in formal or old-fashioned expressions.

The token immediately before the start of the sequence often seems to be "Lady", with the selected text usually including a word that goes with "Lady", such as "Lady of" or "Ladybugs". Additionally, there seems to be a common pattern where the selected word is a preposition, such as "of", "to", "in", or "from".
Titles of nobility or honor, often preceding a person's name, such as "Lord", "Lady", "Sir", "Duke", "Baron", "Count", "Professor", and "President".
References to the White House, its occupants, or related entities, such as the President, First Lady, or Secret Service, often denoted by proper nouns or honorific titles.
